The nominations for the 77th Primetime Emmy Awards were announced on July 15, 2025, at the Television Academy's Wolf Theatre in [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]], hosted by actor [[Harvey Guillén]] and actress [[Brenda Song]], along with Television Academy chair [[Cris Abrego]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Travis |first=Emlyn |title=How to Watch 2025 Emmys Nominations Live |url=https://ew.com/how-to-watch-2025-emmys-nominations-live-11768562 |access-date=September 18, 2025 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250717191258/https://ew.com/how-to-watch-2025-emmys-nominations-live-11768562 |archive-date=July 17, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> The nominees for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Reality Competition Program|Outstanding Reality Competition Program]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Series|Outstanding Talk Series]] were revealed on ''[[CBS Mornings]]'' a few hours prior.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/emmys-reality-talk-nominations-early-cbs-1236460209/ |title=Emmys to Reveal Reality and Talk Series Nominations Early on ''CBS Mornings'' |last=Davis |first=Clayton |access-date=July 15, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918065950/https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/emmys-reality-talk-nominations-early-cbs-1236460209/ |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US \url=status=live}}</ref> Including nominations at the [[77th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]], ''[[Severance (TV series)|Severance]]'' led all programs with 27 nominations, followed by ''[[The Penguin (TV series)|The Penguin]]'' with 24 nominations.<ref>{{cite web |last=Richwine |first=Lisa |title=''Severance'', ''The Penguin'' Lead Nominations for TV's Emmy Awards |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/severance-the-white-lotus-nominated-best-drama-tvs-emmys-2025-07-15/ |access-date=July 23, 2025 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250716200328/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/severance-the-white-lotus-nominated-best-drama-tvs-emmys-2025-07-15/ |archive-date=July 16, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Studio (TV series)|The Studio]]'' became the most-nominated first-year comedy series in the awards' history with 23 nominations; the [[Apple TV (streaming service)|Apple TV+]] comedy surpassed the record held by the sports comedy ''[[Ted Lasso]]'', which received 20 nominations in [[73rd Primetime Emmy Awards|2021]]. The series also tied ''[[The Bear (TV series)|The Bear]]''{{'}}s 23 nominations in the [[76th Primetime Emmy Awards|previous year]] for most nominations for a comedy series in a single season.<ref name="Studio Record">{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Clayton |title='''The Studio'' Breaks ''Ted Lasso'' Emmy Record for Most Nominations for a Freshman Comedy Series, Ties ''The Bear'' for Most in History |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/the-studio-emmys-record-most-nominations-season-1-1236448864/ |access-date=August 1, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250716171450/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/the-studio-emmys-record-most-nominations-season-1-1236448864/ |archive-date=July 16, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Sterling K. Brown]], nominated for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] for his role in ''[[Paradise (2025 TV series)|Paradise]]'', tied with [[Andre Braugher]] and [[Don Cheadle]] for most nominations by a Black male performer with 11 nominations each.<ref>{{cite web |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |title=Emmy On-Screen Diversity Takes a Hit with Acting & Hosting Nominations Down 18% from 2024 |url=https://deadline.com/2025/07/emmy-nominations-2025-diversity-1236458471/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 15, 2025 |access-date=August 28, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250716125717/https://deadline.com/2025/07/emmy-nominations-2025-diversity-1236458471/ |archive-date=July 16, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> At age 77, [[Kathy Bates]] became the oldest nominee for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]] for her performance in ''[[Matlock (2024 TV series)|Matlock]]''; she surpassed the record previously held by [[Angela Lansbury]] who was nominated at age 70 in [[48th Primetime Emmy Awards|1996]] for her role in ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Clayton |title=Kathy Bates Becomes the Oldest Emmy Nominee for Lead Drama Actress |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/kathy-bates-emmys-record-oldest-nominee-1236448948/ |access-date=August 19, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250728061544/https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/kathy-bates-emmys-record-oldest-nominee-1236448948/ |archive-date=July 28, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> At age 21, [[Bella Ramsey]] was the youngest two-time nominee for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series for their performance in ''[[The Last of Us (TV series)|The Last of Us]]''.<ref name="Variety Emmys Diversity Report">{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Clayton |title=Emmys 2025 Diversity Report: Worst Showing for Actors of Color in 5 Years Despite Historic Nominations |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/emmys-2025-diversity-worst-showing-actors-color-1236448971/ |access-date=August 19, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250824110924/https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/emmys-2025-diversity-worst-showing-actors-color-1236448971/ |archive-date=August 24, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Ramsey was also the first openly [[non-binary]] person to be nominated more than once for an acting Emmy.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Mier |first=Tomás |date=July 15, 2025 |title=Bella Ramsey Becomes First Non-Binary Person to Earn Two Emmy Nominations |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-news/bella-ramsey-first-non-binary-earn-two-emmy-nominations-1235386031/ |access-date=September 8, 2025 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250919102248/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-news/bella-ramsey-first-non-binary-earn-two-emmy-nominations-1235386031/ |archive-date=September 19, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> At age 83, for his role on ''[[Shrinking (TV series)|Shrinking]]'', [[Harrison Ford]] became the second oldest nominee for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series behind [[Alan Arkin]], who was nominated in that category at age 86 in [[72nd Primetime Emmy Awards|2020]] for his work on ''[[The Kominsky Method]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Clayton |title=Harrison Ford Lands First Career Emmy Nomination for ''Shrinking'' and Becomes Second Oldest Nominee in Category History |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/harrison-ford-first-emmys-nom-second-oldest-shrinking-1236448941/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250728061434/https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/harrison-ford-first-emmys-nom-second-oldest-shrinking-1236448941/ |archive-date=July 28, 2025 |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Ayo Edebiri]], nominated for both [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]] for her work on ''The Bear'', was the first Black woman nominated for both acting and directing in the same year. At age 29, Edebiri also became the youngest Black woman to receive three acting nominations in her career.<ref name="Variety Emmys Diversity Report"/> For the first time in Emmys history, the nominees for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]] had at least one woman included in each of the writing teams.<ref name="Variety Emmys Diversity Report"/> [[HBO]] and its streaming service [[HBO Max]] led all networks and platforms with 142 nominations; [[Netflix]] came in second place with 120 nominations.<ref>{{cite web |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |title=HBO Max Scores Record Emmy Nominations Haul Fueled by ''The Penguin'', ''The White Lotus'', ''The Last of Us'', and ''Hacks'' |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-nominations-scorecard-hbo-max-netflix-apple-tv-fx-1236460862/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 16, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250716191106/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-nominations-scorecard-hbo-max-netflix-apple-tv-fx-1236460862/ |archive-date=July 16, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

The winners were announced on September 14, following the Creative Arts Emmys on September 6 and 7. With 30 total wins each, HBO and its streaming service HBO Max tied with Netflix to lead all networks and platforms.<ref>{{cite web |last=Haiku |first=Selome |title=''The Studio'' Leads 2025 Emmy Wins While HBO Max and Netflix Tie as Ceremony's Top Platforms |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-2025-hbo-max-netflix-studio-wins-by-show-platform-1236515805/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915163742/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-2025-hbo-max-netflix-studio-wins-by-show-platform-1236515805/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Combined with its nine Creative Arts Emmys, ''The Studio'' was the most awarded comedy in a single year with thirteen wins, breaking ''The Bear''{{'}}s record of eleven from the previous year.<ref>{{cite web |last=Loving |first=Casey |title=''The Studio'' Breaks Comedy Emmys Records Once Held by ''The Bear'' |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-studio-breaks-the-bear-emmy-records-2025/ |access-date=September 16, 2025 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250916233857/https://www.thewrap.com/the-studio-breaks-the-bear-emmy-records-2025/ |archive-date=September 16, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> It also surpassed the record for most wins by a freshman comedy series which was previously set by ''The Bear'' with ten awards in [[75th Primetime Emmy Awards|2023]].<ref name="The Studio">{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Clayton |title=''The Studio'' Makes Emmys History as the Most Awarded Comedy Ever, Seth Rogen Ties for Most Individual Wins in One Night |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/the-studio-emmy-record-1236510814/ |date=September 14, 2025 |access-date=September 15, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918204846/https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/the-studio-emmy-record-1236510814/ |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Seth Rogen won four awards for the aforementioned program to tie [[Moira Demos]], [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]], and [[Amy Sherman-Palladino]] for the most wins for an individual in one year.<ref>{{cite web |last=Moreau |first=Jordan |last2=Otterson |first2=Joe |title=Emmys 2025 Winners: ''The Studio'' Dominates with 13 Wins, ''Adolescence'' and ''The Pitt'' Win Top Honors |url=https://variety.com/lists/emmys-2025-winners-studio-penguin-severance/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915040949/https://variety.com/lists/emmys-2025-winners-studio-penguin-severance/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Pitt]]'' became the first [[medical drama|medical procedural]] to win Outstanding Drama Series since ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jacobs |first=Meredith |title=6 ''ER'' Stars Who Should Appear on ''The Pitt'' Next — And Our Pitched Storylines (Poll) |url=https://www.tvinsider.com/1215632/the-pitt-season-2-er-stars-storylines/ |access-date=September 17, 2025 |work=[[TV Guide (magazine)#TV Insider|TV Insider]] |date=September 16, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918015831/https://www.tvinsider.com/1215632/the-pitt-season-2-er-stars-storylines/ |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Tramell Tillman]] was the first Black performer to win Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series for his work on ''Severance''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Davis |first=Clayton |title=Tramell Tillman Becomes First Black Man to Win Supporting Drama Actor for ''Severance'' |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/tramell-tillman-first-black-supporting-winner-history-1236509585/ |access-date=September 15, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915155029/https://variety.com/2025/tv/awards/tramell-tillman-first-black-supporting-winner-history-1236509585/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> At age 15, for his role in ''[[Adolescence (TV series)|Adolescence]]'', [[Owen Cooper]] became the youngest male acting winner in Emmy history, breaking a record previously held by [[Scott Jacoby (actor)|Scott Jacoby]] who won Outstanding Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role in a Drama in [[25th Primetime Emmy Awards|1973]] at age 16 for ''[[That Certain Summer]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ford |first=Lily |title=''Adolescence'' Star Owen Cooper Makes Emmys History as Youngest-Ever Male Winner in Any Acting Category |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/adolescence-star-owen-cooper-emmys-win-record-breaker-1236369134/ |access-date=September 15, 2025 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250927180527/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/adolescence-star-owen-cooper-emmys-win-record-breaker-1236369134/ |archive-date=September 27, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

Winners are listed first, highlighted in '''boldface''', and indicated with a double dagger (‡).<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/Downloads/77thnominations-list-v4.pdf |title=77th Emmy Awards Complete Nominations List |access-date=September 16, 2025 |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918191722/https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/Downloads/77thnominations-list-v4.pdf |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/press/emmys-240914-v1a.pdf |access-date=September 16, 2025 |title=77th Emmy Awards Winners Announced |date=September 14, 2025 |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250925123643/https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/press/emmys-240914-v1a.pdf |archive-date=September 25, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|The outlets listed for each program are the U.S. broadcasters or streaming services identified in the nominations, which for some international productions are different than the broadcaster(s) that originally commissioned the program. Programs broadcast by [[HBO]] or [[HBO Max]] were listed under both services in the nominations list; only the original broadcaster is listed below.}} For simplicity, producers who received nominations for program awards, as well as nominated writers for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series|Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series]], have been omitted.

