==Ceremony information==
[[File:Nate Bargatze.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Nate Bargatze in 2017.|[[Nate Bargatze]] hosted the ceremony.]]

On March 5, 2025, the [[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]], also known as the Television Academy, announced that the 77th Primetime Emmy Awards would be held on September 14.<ref name="CBS Emmys">{{cite web |last=Petski |first=Denise |title=2025 Emmys Gets Airdate on CBS |url=https://deadline.com/2025/03/2025-emmys-airdate-cbs-1236311538/ |access-date=June 15, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 5, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250403132131/https://deadline.com/2025/03/2025-emmys-airdate-cbs-1236311538/ |archive-date=April 3, 2025 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[CBS]] broadcast the ceremony as part of a rotating deal among the "Big Four" networks ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], CBS, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], and [[NBC]]) signed in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/emmys-renews-big-four-deal-8-years-1132446/ |title=Emmys Renew Big Four Deal for 8 Years |last=O'Connell |first=Mikey |date=August 6, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=December 7, 2021 |archive-date=December 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207184542/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/emmys-renews-big-four-deal-8-years-1132446/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, it was announced that the ceremony would be available live and on-demand via [[Paramount Skydance]]'s streaming service [[Paramount+]].<ref name="CBS Emmys"/> The ceremony was produced by Jesse Collins Entertainment (Jesse Collins, Dionne Harmon, and Jeannae Rouzan-Clay) for the third consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rice |first=Lynette |title=Jesse Collins Entertainment Will Return to Executive Produce the 77th Annual Emmy Awards |url=https://deadline.com/2025/04/jesse-collins-entertainment-will-return-to-executive-produce-the-77th-annual-emmy-awards-1236374896/ |access-date=May 2, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=April 23, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250515164239/https://deadline.com/2025/04/jesse-collins-entertainment-will-return-to-executive-produce-the-77th-annual-emmy-awards-1236374896/ |archive-date=May 15, 2025 |url-status=live}}</ref> On April 16, comedian [[Nate Bargatze]] was announced as the ceremony's host.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jensen |first=Erin |title=Comedian Nate Bargatze is 'Beyond Excited' to Host the 2025 Emmy Awards |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2025/04/16/emmys-2025-host-nate-bargatze/83117224007/ |access-date=May 2, 2025 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=April 16, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250604081729/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2025/04/16/emmys-2025-host-nate-bargatze/83117224007/ |archive-date=June 4, 2025 |url-status=live}}</ref>

During a press conference held on September 11 promoting the show, producer Collins revealed that the ceremony would feature reunions in tribute to the 25th anniversaries of [[The CW]] and [[The WB|WB]] comedy-drama series ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'' and CBS reality competition series ''[[Survivor (American TV series)|Survivor]]'', and the 35th anniversary of NBC's [[police procedural]] franchise ''[[Law & Order (franchise)|Law & Order]]''. Additionally, the telecast would pay tribute to the 40th anniversary of the NBC sitcom ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' with country singer [[Reba McEntire]] and [[Little Big Town]]'s [[Karen Fairchild]] and [[Kimberly Schlapman]] performing the series' theme song, "[[Thank You for Being a Friend]]".<ref>{{cite web |last=Rice |first=Lynette |title=Emmy Producers Promise ''Golden Girls'' Tribute, More Reunions, and Zero Politics: 'We're Just Celebrating Television' |url=https://deadline.com/2025/09/emmy-producers-promise-golden-girl-tribute-more-reunions-1236528891/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 11, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250912114617/https://deadline.com/2025/09/emmy-producers-promise-golden-girl-tribute-more-reunions-1236528891/ |archive-date=September 12, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Eric Dane]] and [[Jesse Williams (actor)|Jesse Williams]] were initially scheduled as co-presenters to honor the 20th anniversary of ABC medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', but Dane was absent from the ceremony while Williams presented alone. According to Collins, he told reporters for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' after the awards ceremony, "I just was told that he wasn't able to make it, and fortunately, Jesse was able to present by himself."<ref>{{cite web |last=Wang |first=Jessica |title=Emmy Producers Address Eric Dane's absence from the Show |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-producers-show-behind-the-scenes-3-1236519345/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915152721/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-producers-show-behind-the-scenes-3-1236519345/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> The following month, Dane revealed during an interview with ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that he was recovering from a fall he suffered in his kitchen shortly before the ceremony. He had previously been diagnosed with [[ALS]] in April 2025.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Galante |first=Grace |title=Eric Dane Reveals Why He Missed the 2025 Emmy Awards |url=https://parade.com/news/eric-dane-reveals-why-he-missed-2025-emmy-awards |magazine=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |access-date=October 3, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251106061417/https://parade.com/news/eric-dane-reveals-why-he-missed-2025-emmy-awards |archive-date=November 6, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

In an effort to shorten winners' acceptance speeches and have the telecast run on time, Bargatze revealed that he would donate $100,000 to the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Club of America]]. However, for every second an award winner's speech went over the 45-second limit $1,000 would be deducted from the donation.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schneider |first=Michael |title=Nate Bargatze and Emmys Team on Security Plans, How They're Keeping the Focus on TV — and If Beyoncé Will Show Up |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/nate-bargatze-emmys-producers-security-plans-beyonce-coming-1236515478/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 11, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250914094838/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/nate-bargatze-emmys-producers-security-plans-beyonce-coming-1236515478/ |archive-date=September 14, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, for every second under the limit another $1,000 would be added.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rice |first=Lynette |title=Emmy Host Nate Bargatze Reveals Novel Way He'll Keep Speeches Short on Sunday That Involves Docking a Donation to Boys & Girls Club |url=https://deadline.com/2025/09/emmy-host-nate-bargatze-keeping-speeches-short-sunday-1236527861/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 10, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250914172113/https://deadline.com/2025/09/emmy-host-nate-bargatze-keeping-speeches-short-sunday-1236527861/ |archive-date=September 14, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of the show, the sum of money slated be donated fell $60,000 below zero due to several winners' speech going over the time limit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boys & Girls Clubs of America May Wind Up Biggest Emmy Winner Thanks to Nate Bargatze's Bit |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/boys-girls-clubs-america-may-wind-biggest-emmy-winner-thanks-nate-barg-rcna231518 |access-date=September 18, 2025 |agency=[[NBC News]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250926235248/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/boys-girls-clubs-america-may-wind-biggest-emmy-winner-thanks-nate-barg-rcna231518 |archive-date=September 26, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, Bargatze stated that CBS would donate the full $100,000 to the charity, and that he would add an additional $250,000.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mulroy |first=Clare |title=How Much Did Emmys Host Nate Bargatze End Up Donating to Boys and Girls Club? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2025/09/15/nate-bargatze-emmys-host-donation/86161971007/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250916163032/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2025/09/15/nate-bargatze-emmys-host-donation/86161971007/ |archive-date=September 16, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

Several other individuals were involved with the production of the telecast. Alex Rudzinski and [[Rickey Minor]] served as director and musical director for the ceremony, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=77th Emmy Awards Program |url=https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/press/emmys-240914-v1a.pdf |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |access-date=September 18, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250904033829/https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/Downloads/77th-emmys-program-v1.pdf |archive-date=September 4, 2025 |page=128 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' co-anchors [[Kevin Frazier]] and [[Nischelle Turner]] hosted a [[red carpet]] pre-show preceding the telecast.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gomez |first=Dessi |title=How to Watch the 2025 Emmys Online and On TV |url=https://deadline.com/2025/09/how-to-watch-2025-emmys-streaming-1236528153/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 10, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250914022206/https://deadline.com/2025/09/how-to-watch-2025-emmys-streaming-1236528153/ |archive-date=September 14, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Comedians [[Mikey Day]], [[James Austin Johnson]], and [[Bowen Yang]] participated in an opening comedy sketch with Bargatze parodying how [[Philo Farnsworth]] invented television, similar to the "Washington's Dream" sketch featured in a [[Saturday Night Live season 50|50th season]] episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shanfield |first=Ethan |title=Nate Bargatze Opens Emmys by Joking CBS Stands for 'Caucasian Broadcast System' and More in 'Inventor of Television' Sketch |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/nate-bargatze-emmys-monologue-2025-1236517956/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915010802/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/nate-bargatze-emmys-monologue-2025-1236517956/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

===Category and rule changes===
On January 8, 2025, the Television Academy announced rule changes that affected the directing and guest performer awards. Starting with the 77th ceremony, individuals or directing teams are permitted to submit multiple episodes for consideration in the directing categories, provided that the episodes are from different programs. In previous years, directors or directing teams could only submit one entry per category.<ref>{{cite web |last=Porter |first=Rick |title=Emmys Modify Rules for Directors, Guest Actors |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/emmy-awards-change-rules-directors-guest-actors-1236104152/ |access-date=March 2, 2025 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 8, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250402203916/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/emmy-awards-change-rules-directors-guest-actors-1236104152/ |archive-date=April 2, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, any performer who previously won or has been nominated in the lead or supporting acting categories would be ineligible to submit a performance of the same character in the same series for consideration in the guest performance categories in subsequent years.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schneider |first=Michael |title=Emmy Rule Changes Revealed by Television Academy: No Guest Star Double Dipping, and More Eligibility for Directors |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-rule-changes-television-academy-guest-star-directors-eligibility-1236269914/ |access-date=March 2, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 8, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250130113404/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmy-rule-changes-television-academy-guest-star-directors-eligibility-1236269914/ |archive-date=January 30, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

On July 22, 2025, it was announced that [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series|Outstanding Writing for a Variety Series]] would be presented at the main ceremony, replacing [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Variety Special|Outstanding Writing for a Variety Special]], which was presented at the Creative Arts ceremony held on September 7.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=Emmys 2025: Category Breakdown by Night Revealed |url=https://deadline.com/2025/07/emmys-2025-category-breakdown-by-night-creative-arts-1236465463/ |access-date=July 29, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 22, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250729083101/https://deadline.com/2025/07/emmys-2025-category-breakdown-by-night-creative-arts-1236465463/ |archive-date=July 29, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Two weeks later, the Television Academy moved the presentation for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Special (Live)|Outstanding Variety Special (Live)]] to the main ceremony as well.<ref>{{cite web |last=White |first=Peter |title=Emmys Shakeup: Beyoncé & ''SNL50'' Go Primetime as TV Academy Adds Live Variety Special Category to Main Telecast |url=https://deadline.com/2025/08/emmys-beyonce-snl50-live-variety-special-primetime-1236478660/ |access-date=August 5, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 5, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250808121220/https://deadline.com/2025/08/emmys-beyonce-snl50-live-variety-special-primetime-1236478660/ |archive-date=August 8, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

===Critical reviews and viewership===
The broadcast generally received mixed to negative reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Emmys: 77th Emmys Reviews |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/emmys/s77/reviews |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=September 18, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250922052155/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/emmys/s77/reviews |archive-date=September 22, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Aramide Tinubu, writing for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', found the onslaught of surprise winners adding to the excitement, but criticized host Bargatze's performance and wrote, "He lacked the enthusiasm and gumption needed to lead a three-hour-long award program and often seemed stunned to be in the spotlight." She also noted that the decision to have a forty-five second acceptance speech rule to caused winners to hurriedly rush through their speeches while contrasting that with presenters' introductions that seemed to drag down the ceremony.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tinubu |first=Aranide |title=The Emmys' Exciting Wins Were Overshadowed by an Uninspiring Host and Countdown-Clock Gimmick: TV Review |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmys-2025-review-nate-bargatze-host-fails-1236518864/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918144546/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmys-2025-review-nate-bargatze-host-fails-1236518864/ |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Daniel Feinberg of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote, "It was an ill-conceived mess, punctuated by well-deserved wins and emotional and effective speeches, but rarely helped by Bargatze's consistently uneasy performance."<ref>{{cite web |last=Fienberg |first=Daniel |title=Critic's Notebook: A Flat Nate Bargatze and a Failed Time-Saving Gag Upstage Worthy Winners at the Emmy Awards |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-reviews/2025-emmys-critics-analysis-nate-bargatze-adolescence-1236371441/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915070741/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-reviews/2025-emmys-critics-analysis-nate-bargatze-adolescence-1236371441/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Brian Lowry of ''[[TheWrap]]'' commented, "Unfortunately, racing through the speeches came at too high a cost for the show itself, one that played out in uneven pacing and awkward moments strewn throughout." He concluded that due to the time limit, the ceremony was "an otherwise bland affair, which, one suspects, is just the way the Television Academy wanted it."<ref>{{cite web |last=Lowry |first=Brian |title=Emmys Review: Speeding Up the Acceptance Speeches Came at a Too-High Cost |url=https://www.thewrap.com/emmys-2025-review-speeches/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915055500/https://www.thewrap.com/emmys-2025-review-speeches/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

In a more positive review, Robert Lloyd of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' complimented the show and wrote of host Bargatze, "If your goal was to avoid insulted celebrities, social media outrage or petulant notes from the White House, you could have done no better than to hire Bargatze, a clean, calm, classical, noncontroversial, nonpolitical, very funny, very successful comedian." He also reserved praise for several presenters, including [[Stephen Colbert]], [[Brad Garrett]], and [[Ray Romano]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |title=Emmy Awards Host Nate Bargatze Kept the Show Running and Paid the Price — for a Good Cause |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2025-09-14/emmy-awards-2025-broadcast-review-nate-bargatze |access-date=September 18, 2025 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250920135258/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2025-09-14/emmy-awards-2025-broadcast-review-nate-bargatze |archive-date=September 20, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> Matt Roush of ''[[TV Guide (magazine)#TV Insider|TV Insider]]'' wrote, "There was a sense that for all of the ribbing, this Emmys broadcast was a pleasurable celebration of an ever-evolving medium." He also gave high marks toward Bargatze, but criticized the acceptance speech 45-second rule as tiresome.<ref>{{cite web |last=Roush |first=Matt |title=Critic's Notebook: Surprises Galore in a Fast-Moving Emmy Show |url=https://www.tvinsider.com/1215295/emmys-2025-review/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[TV Guide (magazine)#TV Insider|TV Insider]] |date=September 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918091559/https://www.tvinsider.com/1215295/emmys-2025-review/ |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> David Nemetz of ''[[TVLine]]'' wrote, "These Emmys were strangely anti-TV at times, with a self-deprecating tone that bordered on masochistic. But they also showcased the best that TV has to offer, with surprise wins and stirring speeches that reminded us of the sheer quantity of top-notch programming we're blessed to have at our fingertips right now."<ref>{{cite web |last=Nemetz |first=Dave |title=Emmys 2025 Review: A Chaotic Night Manages to Honor Television's Best and Slam Them, Too |url=https://tvline.com/reviews/emmys-2025-review-1235513921/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[TVLine]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250920194220/https://tvline.com/reviews/emmys-2025-review-1235513921/ |archive-date=September 20, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

The ceremony was viewed by 7.59&nbsp;million people in the United States, making it the most-viewed Emmys in [[73rd Primetime Emmy Awards|four years]], representing a 10% increase over the previous year's ceremony.<ref name="Emmy Ratings">{{cite web |last=Porter |first=Rick |title=TV Ratings: Emmy Awards Hit Four-Year High |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/emmys-2025-tv-ratings-1236371769/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918072339/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/emmys-2025-tv-ratings-1236371769/ |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref> It also achieved a 1.28 rating among adults ages 18–49.<ref name="Emmy Ratings"/> Ratings figures included those who watched the telecast on CBS or streamed it on Paramount+.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hailu |first=Selome |title=Emmys Hit 7.4 Million Viewers, Most-Watched Ceremony Since 2021 |url=https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmys-2025-ratings-1236519497/ |access-date=September 18, 2025 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 15, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250915205359/https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/emmys-2025-ratings-1236519497/ |archive-date=September 15, 2025 |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref>

==In Memoriam==
The annual In Memoriam segment was presented by [[Phylicia Rashad]], and featured [[Vince Gill]] and [[Lainey Wilson]] performing Gill's song "[[Go Rest High on That Mountain]]".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pedersen |first1=Erik |last2=Gomez |first2=Dessi |title=''The Pitt'' Takes Drama Series & ''The Studio'' Tops Comedy as ''Adolescence'' Leads the Field – Full Winners List |url=https://deadline.com/lists/emmys-2025-winners-list/writing-limited-anthology-series-emmy-winner-2025/ |access-date=September 17, 2025 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 14, 2025 |archive-date=September 24, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250924054419/https://deadline.com/lists/emmys-2025-winners-list/writing-limited-anthology-series-emmy-winner-2025/ |language=en-US |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0JbwPS2Ic8g |title=In Memoriam: 77th Emmy Awards |date=September 14, 2025 |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |access-date=September 18, 2025 |via=[[YouTube]] |archive-date=September 18, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250918200341/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0JbwPS2Ic8g |url-status=live}}</ref>

